Observation Details: Calls recorded and will be attached. Very close looks at this flycatcher from about 20 feet away, as it landed in a tree only about 10 feet from me down low. Spooked when I raised binoculars, but only flew about 10 feet higher and allowed best views I've had of this species in many years. The gray around the neck and chest area was so dark it was almost blue and the yellow below was very bright, with a hint of cinnamon brown in the wings. A stunning bird at close range and one that is most likely a migrant as they don't seem to nest anywhere close to here.

These are quite uncommon in the county so I was very surprised to hear what sounded like one calling in the backyard. I went out to chase it down and it was in the grove of tall oak trees in the back yard, flying out to catch bugs and then back into the trees. I was able to get a definitive look at a yellowish bellied and brown topped bird with a fluffy crest, but only for a few seconds. Interestingly, this bird is 2 years to the day after my last in-county sighting and at the same place too. Gave the strong clear rising sheeep call, but only a few times.
